# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: line-area-charts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] An **area chart** or **area graph** displays graphically quantitative data.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] The area between axis and line are commonly emphasized with colors, textures and hatchings.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] Commonly one compares two or more quantities with an area chart.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] William Playfair is usually credited with inventing the area charts as well as the line, bar, and pie charts.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] Area charts are used to represent cumulated totals using numbers or percentages (stacked area charts in this case) over time.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] Use the area chart for showing trends over time among related attributes.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] The area chart is like the plot chart except that the area below the plotted line is filled in with color to indicate volume.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] When multiple attributes are included, the first attribute is plotted as a line with color fill followed by the second attribute, and so on.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] Area charts which use vertical and horizontal lines to connect the data points in a series forming a step-like progression are called *step-area charts*.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] Area charts in which data points are connected by smooth curves instead of straight lines are called *spline-area charts*.
[src:line-area-charts/area-chart] Stacked area charts in which the area is displaced around the central axis are called *streamgraphs*.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] A **fan chart** is made of a group of dispersion fan diagrams, which may be positioned according to two categorising dimensions.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] A *dispersion fan diagram* is a circular diagram which reports the same information about a dispersion as a box plot: namely median, quartiles, and two extreme values.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] 4. two *feathers* which indicate the extreme values.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The scale on the circular line begins at the left with the starting value (e. g. with zero).
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The following values are applicated clockwise.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The white tail of diameter indicates the median.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The dark fan indicates the dispersion of the middle half of the observed values; thus it encompasses the values from the first to the third quartile.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The white feathers indicate the dispersion of the middle 90% of the observed values.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The length of the white part of the diameter corresponds with the number of observations.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] A fan chart gives a quick summary of observed values which depend from two variables.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] This is possible thanks of a dense representation and a constant size which does not depend on the size of the single dispersion fan diagrams.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] An essential advantage compared to a sequence of box plots is the possibility to compare dispersion fan diagrams not only within one direction but within two directions (horizontally and vertically).
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The following example presents data from the data set *MathAchieve* which is part of the R package *nlme* of José Pinheiro et al.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] It contains mathematics achievement scores of 7185 students.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The students are categorised according to sex and membership of a minority ethnic group.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The graphics show the mathematics achievement scores in dependency on the socio-economic status of the students (x axis) and on the average socio-economic status of all students at the same school (y axis).
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The four graphic panels differentiate the students according to sex and membership of a minority ethnic group.
[src:line-area-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The fan charts reveals clearly how the median value is partially following a big main tendency while the values of the single subgroups (with the cells) scatter largely what could lead to doubts about a possible correlation.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] A **line chart** or **line graph**, also known as **curve chart**, is a type of chart that displays information as a series of data points called 'markers' connected by straight line segments.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] It is a basic type of chart common in many fields.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] It is similar to a scatter plot except that the measurement points are ordered (typically by their x-axis value) and joined with straight line segments.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] A line chart is often used to visualize a trend in data over intervals of time – a time series – thus the line is often drawn chronologically.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] In these cases they are known as run charts.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Some of the earliest known line charts are generally credited to Francis Hauksbee, Nicolaus Samuel Cruquius, Johann Heinrich Lambert and the Scottish engineer William Playfair.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Line charts often display time as a variable on the x-axis.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Playfair was one of the first to visualize data this way.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] In 1786, he plotted ten years of money spent by the Royal Navy.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] He supplemented the chart with a detailed description, telling his readers how to interpret the change over time because they were unfamiliar with this form of abstract visualization.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] In addition to line charts, Playfair invented and popularized bar charts and pie charts.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] In the experimental sciences, data collected from experiments are often visualized by a graph.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Such a table representation of data is a great way to display exact values, but it can prevent the discovery and understanding of patterns in the values.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] In addition, a table display is often erroneously considered to be an objective, neutral collection or storage of the data (and may in that sense even be erroneously considered to be the data itself) whereas it is in fact just one of various possible visualizations of the data.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Understanding the process described by the data in the table is aided by producing a graph or line chart of *speed versus time*.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Such a visualisation appears in the figure to the right.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] This visualization can let the viewer quickly understand the entire process at a glance.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] This visualization can however be misunderstood, especially when expressed as showing the mathematical function $v(t)$ that expresses the speed v (the dependent variable) as a function of time t .
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] This can be misunderstood as showing speed to be a variable that is dependent only on time.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] This would however only be true in the case of an object being acted on only by a constant force acting in a vacuum.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Charts often include an overlaid mathematical function depicting the best-fit trend of the scattered data.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] This layer is referred to as a best-fit layer and the graph containing this layer is often referred to as a line graph.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] It is highly unlikely that the experimental error in the data is negligible, yet the curve falls exactly through each of the data points.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] In either case, the best-fit layer can reveal trends in the data.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Further, measurements such as the gradient or the area under the curve can be made visually, leading to more conclusions or results from the data table.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] A true best-fit layer should depict a continuous mathematical function whose parameters are determined by using a suitable error-minimization scheme, which appropriately weights the error in the data values.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Such curve fitting functionality is often found in graphing software or spreadsheets.
[src:line-area-charts/line-chart] Best-fit curves may vary from simple linear equations to more complex quadratic, polynomial, exponential, and periodic curves.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **spline interpolation** is a form of interpolation where the interpolant is a special type of piecewise polynomial called a spline.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] Spline interpolation is often preferred over polynomial interpolation because the interpolation error can be made small even when using low-degree polynomials for the spline.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] Spline interpolation also avoids the problem of Runge's phenomenon, in which oscillation can occur between points when interpolating using high-degree polynomials.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] Originally, *spline* was a term for elastic rulers that were bent to pass through a number of predefined points, or *knots*.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] These were used to make technical drawings for shipbuilding and construction by hand, as illustrated in the figure.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] We wish to model similar kinds of curves using a set of mathematical equations.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] There will be a cubic polynomial $q_{i}(x)=y$ between each successive pair of knots $(x_{i-1},y_{i-1})$ and $(x_{i},y_{i})$ connecting to both of them, where $i=1,2,\dots ,n$ .
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] So there will be n polynomials, with the first polynomial starting at $(x_{0},y_{0})$ , and the last polynomial ending at $(x_{n},y_{n})$ .
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] where $y'$ and $y''$ are the first and second derivatives of $y(x)$ with respect to x .
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] To make the spline take a shape that minimizes the bending (under the constraint of passing through all knots), we will define both $y'$ and $y''$ to be continuous everywhere, including at the knots.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] This can only be achieved if polynomials of degree 3 (cubic polynomials) or higher are used.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] The classical approach is to use polynomials of exactly degree 3 — cubic splines.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] In addition to the three conditions above, a *natural cubic spline* has the condition that $q''_{1}(x_{0})=q''_{n}(x_{n})=0$ .
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] In addition to the three main conditions above, a *clamped cubic spline* has the conditions that $q'_{1}(x_{0})=f'(x_{0})$ and $q'_{n}(x_{n})=f'(x_{n})$ where $f'(x)$ is the derivative of the interpolated function.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] To do this, we will consider just a single piece of the curve, $q(x)$ , which will interpolate from $(x_{1},y_{1})$ to $(x_{2},y_{2})$ .
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] This piece will have slopes $k_{1}$ and $k_{2}$ at its endpoints.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] If the sequence *k*0, *k*1, ..., *kn* is such that, in addition, *q′′i*(*xi*) = *q′′**i*+1(*xi*) holds for *i* = 1, ..., *n* − 1, then the resulting function will even have a continuous second derivative.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] For the elastic rulers being the model for the spline interpolation, one has that to the left of the left-most "knot" and to the right of the right-most "knot" the ruler can move freely and will therefore take the form of a straight line with *q′′* = 0.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] There exist other end conditions, "clamped spline", which specifies the slope at the ends of the spline, and the popular "not-a-knot spline", which requires that the third derivative is also continuous at the *x*1 and *x**n*−1 points.
[src:line-area-charts/spline-interpolation] In the figure, the spline function consisting of the two cubic polynomials $q_{1}(x)$ and $q_{2}(x)$ given by (**9**) is displayed.
[src:line-area-charts/step-function] In mathematics, a function on the real numbers is called a **step function** if it can be written as a finite linear combination of indicator functions of intervals.
[src:line-area-charts/step-function] Informally speaking, a step function is a piecewise constant function having only finitely many pieces.
[src:line-area-charts/step-function] Indeed, if that is not the case to start with, a different set of intervals can be picked for which these assumptions hold.
[src:line-area-charts/step-function] Sometimes, the intervals are required to be right-open or allowed to be singleton.
[src:line-area-charts/step-function] The condition that the collection of intervals must be finite is often dropped, especially in school mathematics, though it must still be locally finite, resulting in the definition of piecewise constant functions.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:line-area-charts/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
